SIMPLE: haunch
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Haunch
<hw>Haunch</hw> <pr>(h⟦aum⟧nch; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>hanche</ets>, of German origin; cf. OD. <ets>hancke</ets>,
<ets>hencke</ets>, and also OHG. <ets>ancha</ets>; prob. not akin to E.
<ets>ankle</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The hip; the projecting region
of the lateral parts of the pelvis and the hip joint; the hind
part.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of meats: The leg and loin taken together; <as>as, a
<ex>haunch</ex> of venison</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Haunch bone</b></col>. <cd>See <cref>Innominate
bone</cref>, under <er>Innominate</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Haunches of an
arch</b></col> <fld>(Arch.)</fld>, <cd>the parts on each side of the
crown of an arch. (See <er>Crown</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 11.) Each
<xex>haunch</xex> may be considered as from one half to two thirds of
the half arch.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Haunched</ent>⟦br⟧
